text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!IndigenousLanguagesOfTheAmericas]]%0a%0a!The Chitimacha Tribe's language%0a%0a:Author: Thomas_H_K%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aInformation about the Chitimacha in present-day Louisiana%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aThe Sovereign Nation of the Chitimacha is located in southern Lousiana.%0a%0aI chose to look in the area around New Orleans for a couple reasons: I saw not many people had picked from the southeast U.S; I was born in New Orleans and have an impression of it as an area fairly distinct from other American cultural groups; I wanted to see how Indigenous cultures were treated in the area.%0a%0aThe Chitmacha have, according to oral history, always lived in the area which is now Louisiana. There is no information on if there are other names for the tribe, and there is no information about the proper pronunciation of the name.%0a%0aThey were subject to U.S.C Title 25 after the Lousiana Purchase, but there are no treaties on the land. Currently, the tribe is a sovereign nation; they own their land, half of which is in a trust.%0a%0aThe language is considered ‘revived’ by the tribe: the last two fluent speakers died in 1932 and 1940, but because the speakers recorded over 200 hours of conversation with a linguist, the language was preserved. Through funding from a grant from RosettaStone, the language has been revived and is available to learn as software to any interested tribal members and is also taught at the tribal school. There is no information about how the language is currently used.%0a %0aSecond Pass of Information: %0a%0aThe IPA transcription of the tribe name is /tʃɪtɪməʃɑː/. The language is referred to as ‘Chitimacha Tribe’s language’ in both indigenous and non-indigenous sources.%0a%0aWikipedia paints the Chitimacha Tribe as much more bystanders in the revival of their language - more credit is given to the linguist who recorded the conversations and the American Philosophical Society Library.  %0a%0aThe language is also described as ‘extinct’ rather than received in secondary sources.%0a%0aThe indigenous run source gives a much more detailed account of how they were forced to sell off their land because of taxes from the US government, which secondary sources do not mention.%0a%0aIndigenous-run source: %0ahttp://www.chitimacha.gov/history-culture%0a%0aSecondary sources: %0ahttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chitimacha%0ahttps://www.cajuncoast.com/about-us/history/history-chitimacha%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a#foxbegin 210412-221659-96580#%0a(:if1 equal {$:Author} {$Author}:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a(:if1end:)%0a#foxend 210412-221659-96580#%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: :)%0a(:Category: IndigenousLanguagesOfTheAmericas:)
